> Hello Sherri,
>
> I've gone down this road (I put a '71 camper interior in a '73) and I can
> offer you a few tips.  I'd second Rik's comments in general.  But
especially
> about the icebox he's correct;  they're worthless, badly designed, etc.
But
> I still have mine in the bus.  Why?  They've got a little flip-up table on
> the door side that is so handy when camping, I put up with it the rest of
> the time.  But, then, maybe I can mount that table behind the passenger
> seat.... hmmm....
>
> Try Wally Mart for some off the rack curtains.  I (and you) probably could
> learn to sew, but it was just easier to put something up that way.
>
> Look around for an older camper interior;  when the rest of the bus is
> rusted beyond help, you can sometimes find someone (like I did) who will
> sell you the whole thing for a hundred bucks or so (for "parts") because
> they are focused on the rusted-out front beam and are not thinking about
the
> camper interior.  Then you can, as Rik says, pull out and use and
customize
> it to whatever you want.  ("Westfakia")
>
> The jump seat is Very Cool;  not for sitting on, but for the storage area
> underneath and behind the back of the seat.
>
> I put the spare tire on the front of the bus;  the wheel well were it sat
is
> a great storage area for tools,  jacks, etc.
>
> The second battery question has taken on the dimensions of a religious
> argument (like tires and oil - see archives).  I had another car battery
> around, so I wired it up, using the Hella relay from BusDepot.  I suppose
if
> you have the money, a deep cycle battery is nice, but if I wait for
> everything to be perfect before I get out and use the bus, I'll still be
in
> my driveway.  8^)
>
> Welcome Buster!
>
> -Bruce M.
> '73 auto
> Cooperstown, New York
>
>
